class Solution {
    public int maxLengthBetweenEqualCharacters(String s) {
        int[] first = new int[26];
        java.util.Arrays.fill(first, -1);
        int max = -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            int c = s.charAt(i) - 'a';
            if (first[c] == -1) {
                first[c] = i;
            } else {
                max = Math.max(max, i - first[c] - 1);
            }
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Single pass records first occurrence of each character; subsequent occurrences compute substring length in constant time. Uses fixed-size array for 26 letters, so space is O(1).

